# 🚀 Day 07 – Linux File System Hierarchy & Scenario-Based Practice

## ✅ What I Learned Today

Today I focused on understanding the Linux File System Hierarchy and how a DevOps Engineer approaches troubleshooting.

### 📂 Linux File System Hierarchy

I explored the purpose of these important directories:

* `/` – Root directory, the starting point of the Linux file system.
* `/home` – Stores user home directories.
* `/root` – Home directory of the root user.
* `/etc` – Contains system configuration files.
* `/var/log` – Stores application and system log files.
* `/tmp` – Used for temporary files.
* `/bin` – Essential Linux commands.
* `/usr/bin` – User-installed command binaries.
* `/opt` – Optional and third-party applications.

### 💻 Hands-on Practice

I practiced the following commands:

```bash
ls -l /
ls -l /home
ls -l /etc
cat /etc/hostname
ls -l /var/log
du -sh /var/log/* | sort -h | tail -5
ls -la ~
which ls
```

### 🔧 Scenario-Based Troubleshooting

Today I also practiced solving common Linux troubleshooting scenarios:

✅ Diagnosing a service that fails to start

```bash
systemctl status <service>
journalctl -u <service> -n 50
systemctl is-enabled <service>
```

✅ Finding processes using high CPU

```bash
top
ps aux --sort=-%cpu | head -10
```

✅ Viewing service logs

```bash
journalctl -u ssh -n 50
journalctl -u ssh -f
```

✅ Fixing file permission issues

```bash
ls -l backup.sh
chmod +x backup.sh
./backup.sh
```

## 🎯 Key Takeaways

* Every Linux system follows a hierarchical directory structure.
* Configuration files are mainly stored in `/etc`.
* Logs are stored in `/var/log`, making them the first place to check during troubleshooting.
* Understanding where files live makes debugging much faster.
* Troubleshooting is about following a logical process, not memorizing commands.

